1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. d5 { A good move and likely what I would do with White, but most London players are attached to their triangle setup. } 3... b5 { I like this move, going for a Benko Gambit-like setup. We're thinking about surrounding the d-pawn. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gc8b7,Gb7d5] } (3... Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Bd2 { I wouldn't recommend grabbing this pawn - White gets good compensation. } { [%cal Ga1b1,Ge2e4] }) 4. c4 (4. a4 b4 5. c4 d6 { With a strategic battle ahead. The break ...e5 can be a good way to gain space in the center. } { [%cal Ge7e5] }) (4. e3 Qa5+ { Defending the b5 pawn with tempo. } 5. c3 Bb7 { White is having problems defending the d5 pawn. } 6. d6 exd6 7. Bxd6 Qb6! 8. Bxf8 Kxf8 { Black has a big lead in development and the king will be safe on g7. } { [%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] }) 4... g6 (4... bxc4?! 5. Nc3 { This gives White easy development and central control. } { [%cal Ge2e4,Gf1c4] }) 5. cxb5 a6 6. bxa6 Bg7 { With a Benko where White has played the not-very-helpful Bf4. } { [%cal Ge8g8,Gc8a6] } *


